        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Array Configuration: We need an angular resolution of ~0.32" (similar to that of our VLA and CARMA observations) and which is sensitive to extended emission at scales up to 5". This configuration gives us the best compromise in order to separate emission from all the individual protostars (minimum separation is 1" between IRS 2A and IRS 2B), to resolve the structure of the IRS 3 disk (our previous modelling predicts a size of ~0.6" at 0.8~mm), and to detect extended emission from the extended jets/outflows (a few arcsecs).

Spectral Setup: We will use four spectral windows at band 7 with bandwidth of 1.875 GHz, dual polarization, and spectral resolution of 1.13 MHz (~1 km/s). We will cover the frequency ranges 344.2 -- 347.9 GHz (lower sideband) and 356.2 -- 359.9 (upper sideband). These ranges include the CO (3-2) and SiO (nu=0; 8-7) in the lower sideband, and HCO+ (4-3) in the upper sideband. With this setup we have a large bandwidth (~7 GHz) to detect the continuum from the line-free channels with a good S/N in a relatively small amount of time. At the same time, the spectral resolution of 1 km/s is good enough to detect outflowing gas at high velocities (&gt;=10 km/s; e.g. Buckle et al. 2010). 

Sensitivity: Previous single-dish submillimeter observations of the CO (3-2) line (beam ~14") (Buckle et al. 2010) measured high-velocity (+-20 km/s) emission with intensities of ~80 Jy/beam. This implies that we need a sensitivity of ~4.2 mJy/beam to detect that high-velocity emission with a beam of ~0.32" at a signal to noise ratio of 10, which can be achieved with an observing time of 2.5 h (including overheads). With this time, we expect to reach an rms noise of ~0.05 mJy/beam in the continuum data which will be enough to detect emission from all the protostars in the field (from our previous CARMA continuum observations, Carrasco-Gonz\'alez et al. 2012, the minimum expected flux density of the protostars at 0.8~mm is ~100 mJy/beam for the weakest sources, IRS 2A and 2B). This continuum rms noise will also allow us to detect emission from the IRS~3 disk (which we expect to resolve; see above) with enough S/N to distinguish between the different disk models obtained from our previous modelling (see Figure 3). 
 
Pointings: Since the primary beam of band 7 is ~15", in order to observe all the sources in the field, we need two pointings, separated by ~11" (one pointing centered on VLA 1 to include also IRS 1 and IRS 3, and the other pointing at position in between IRS 2A and IRS 2B; see Figure 1).
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
