    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose ALMA observations of NGC 2071, the best example of a cluster of YSOs in an intermediate-mass star-forming region containing different disk-protostar-jet systems at scales of few hundred AU. These objects are located in a small region of ~10'' (~3900 AU) size, and seem to be in different evolutionary stages. We propose to perform observations at band 7, which will allow us to conclusively obtain the spectral energy distributions for the different YSOs in the cluster. The ALMA observations, together with our previous VLA and CARMA observations, will allow us to model the emission for each object, and thus to obtain their physical parameters (stellar masses, disk rotation, disk masses, accretion rates, outflow energy) with high accuracy, studying their dependence with the different evolutionary stages of the objects, without any bias due to the distance (all of them embedded in the same molecular cloud). We anticipate tha ALMA will reveal that the youngest protostar in the region will show the highest accretion rate, while the relatively more evolved protostar will show the lowest accretion rate.
</prp:abstract>
